issue.title: Inpainting does not generate comparable results as in A1111

labels.name: can't-reproduce
labels.description: I can't reproduce this, so I can't fix it. Add steps for reproduction and remove this tag.

issue.body:
So i have an issue to use this plugin for inpainting. 
I have an excellent inpaint model that generates very good results in a1111, often even with the first shot. It is very good to adapt to lighting and so on. I use it mainly for faces. The results are always fitting to the tone and lighting of the image and is very easy to use. Even without prompt it does an excellent job. Prompts are only necessary if i want to change some elements. I also don't use any additional plugin. It just works.

However, with this plugin the results are very different in photoshop using the lasso tool. Rectangular selection wont work at all. The first issue is denoising strength. If i use lower than around 0.8 i get a greyish blurry mess that does not resemble the input image at all. With 1.0 i kind of get a result that fits into the image but the outcome is of course very random and the color and lighting is very unsatisfying. In a1111 I normally use 0.3 - 0.7 but these values wont produce anything usable in photoshop with this plugin. 
I also use inpainting sometimes to fix some minor ugly spots, but this does not work if i have to work with full denoising strength.

It turns out that my previous practice is faster and produces better results. For a face change i mark the area and copy paste it into a1111 and paste the restult from the folder back to the image. As i don't change the edges of the image it fits perfectly. Even though this is more manual work it is faster than fiddling with the plugin and does produce so much better results without any issue.

Is there any advice what i might be overlooking? It seems to me what i do normally is actually kind of similar what the plugin does, but not to the same results.

Thanks

comment.body:
> cfg scale 7-10, step 40

No the model likes lower cfg scales and 30 steps with that sampler is totally fine. But I tried it nonetheless with another picture and the result was the same, even worse. The denoising is the problem and not working as expected. With default 0.7 it came out much darker and not fitting at all like in the example and 1.0 kind of worked but the lighting was off. You even see where the mask ended on the neck

![image](https://github.com/AbdullahAlfaraj/Auto-Photoshop-StableDiffusion-Plugin/assets/131664307/19f0d889-c976-490b-b11e-9ed94774f0e4)

![image](https://github.com/AbdullahAlfaraj/Auto-Photoshop-StableDiffusion-Plugin/assets/131664307/f099489f-7711-4dc3-8e4b-8e6d156699ea)


Not sure what is wrong there but it seems the plugin fails to get the context of the picture. I don't even know how that works normally but with this model you can get results without any prompt, it picks up what is on the image and does something that might fit. I mean that is how reg fill from Adobe is working as well.

comment.body:
Ok here are examples. The model used is _epicrealism_pureEvolutionV5-inpainting_.
The example picture is pre downscaled to 683x1024.
Both examples are the first shots i made with this picture, but I tested more with the PS plugin and i did not manage to produce anything better with the PS plugin.

a1111 example

![image](https://github.com/AbdullahAlfaraj/Auto-Photoshop-StableDiffusion-Plugin/assets/131664307/4311794a-5cf1-44cb-a1d1-06fb6fdf1100)

PS example

As I said initially, when I work on high res pictures I cut out the part i want to change, paste it to a1111 and put it back in the picture afterwards. As far as I understand this is kind of similar what the plugin in PS does. But even without the context of the full picture, a1111 does a great job with shadows and tone.
